      <p class="lead drop-cap">Shan Tuyet ancient tea is one of Vietnam's most distinctive agricultural products. Grown wild on 200+ year-old tea trees in the misty highlands of Ha Giang province, these hand-picked leaves yield a tea of remarkable smoothness and depth — a product that Greenie Vietnam now brings to global premium tea retailers and private label brands.</p>

      <h2>The Old Growth</h2>
      <p>These are not plantation rows of waist-high shrubs. Shan Tuyet trees stand 4 to 12 meters tall — true forest sentinels with trunks thick as ancient oaks, their canopies interweaving with wild orchids, epiphytic ferns, and the velvet moss unique to Ha Giang's limestone karst.</p>

      <aside class="side-note">
        <strong>Dendrological Heritage</strong>
        Core samples from the oldest specimens in Hoang Su Phi district confirm a minimum age of 270 years. These trees were already mature when the Tay Son Rebellion reshaped Vietnam in the 18th century.
      </aside>

      <p>The H'Mông and Dao ethnic communities who tend these trees do not farm them in any conventional sense. They are guardians of a wild ecosystem, harvesting only the "one bud, two leaves" standard — a protocol that respects the tree's physiological limits and ensures continued vitality.</p>

      <p>At 1,200 to 1,800 meters above sea level, the trees endure winters where temperatures approach freezing on the highest ridges, only to be enveloped by thick montane clouds for up to 240 days per year. This perpetual altitude stress slows leaf metabolism dramatically, concentrating amino acids, catechins, and volatile aromatic compounds to levels rarely seen in cultivated teas.</p>

      <!-- Pull Quote -->
      <div class="pull-quote">
